    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-03T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-03T13:00:00-05:00" n="69"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d69">
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">No. 69</seg>
                </opener>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">850.33/12–351: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France (</hi>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BDKE1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bruce</hi>
                    </persName>
                    <hi rend="italic">) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d69fn1">Repeated to London for <persName corresp="#p_GWS1"
                            >Gifford</persName>, Bonn for <persName corresp="#p_MJJ1"
                            >McCloy</persName>, and Rome priority for Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>, who was attending the Eighth
                        Session of the North Atlantic Council.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-03T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 3, 1951—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3301. <gloss target="#t_EMBTEL1">Embtel</gloss> 3232, Nov 30, 1 p.m.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d69fn2">Not printed.</note> I talked to <persName corresp="#p_MR1"
                        >Rene Mayer</persName> this morning about the <persName corresp="#p_SR1"
                        >Schuman</persName> Plan. He said that he was confident it wld be ratified
                    by Parliament. Later in day I had long talk with <persName corresp="#p_MG1">Guy
                        Mollet</persName> on same subj. <persName corresp="#p_MG1">Mollet</persName>
                    told me that executive comite of Socialist Party had entrusted him with decision
                    as to how most of the members shld vote on <persName corresp="#p_SR1"
                        >Schuman</persName> Plan. He said they had abandoned their idea of insisting
                    on reservations which wld require another conf between member states. They wld
                    express their reservations in course of debate, but the only formal action they
                    wld demand of French Govt wld be in regard to continuance of present investment
                    program for French coal and steel industries. This he said was a matter that he
                    had reason believe wld be acceptable to <persName corresp="#p_PR2"
                        >Pleven</persName>. It wld require an understanding between the govt and
                    Socialist Party and wld not be made a condition of the treaty. He therefore felt
                    that Socialists cld go ahead and vote freely for ratification which he said he
                    considered a certainty.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BDKE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
